VSo for any of us in this room today, let's start out by admitting we're lucky.
p4
aVWe don't live in the world our mothers lived in,
p5
aVour grandmothers lived in,
p6
aVwhere career choices for women were so limited.
p7
aVAnd if you're in this room today,
p8
aVmost of us grew up in a world where we have basic civil rights,
p9
aVand amazingly, we still live in a world where some women don't have them.
p10
aVBut all that aside, we still have a problem,
p11
aVand it's a real problem.
p12
aVAnd the problem is this:
p13
aVWomen are not making it to the top of any profession
p14
aVanywhere in the world.
p15
aVThe numbers tell the story quite clearly.
p16
aV190 heads of state \u2014 nine are women.
p17
aVOf all the people in parliament in the world,
p18
aV13 percent are women.
p19
aVIn the corporate sector, women at the top,
p20
aVC-level jobs, board seats \u2014
p21
aVtops out at 15, 16 percent.
p22
aVThe numbers have not moved since 2002
p23
aVand are going in the wrong direction.
p24
aVAnd even in the non-profit world,
p25
aVa world we sometimes think of as being led by more women,
p26
aVwomen at the top: 20 percent.
p27
aa(lp28
VWe also have another problem,
p29
aVwhich is that women face harder choices
p30
aVbetween professional success and personal fulfillment.
p31
aVA recent study in the U.S. showed that, of married senior managers,
p32
aVtwo-thirds of the married men had children
p33
aVand only one-third of the married women had children.
p34
aVA couple of years ago, I was in New York,
p35
aVand I was pitching a deal,
p36
aVand I was in one of those fancy New York private equity offices
p37
aVyou can picture.
p38
aVAnd I'm in the meeting \u2014 it's about a three-hour meeting \u2014
p39
aVand two hours in, there needs to be that bio break,
p40
aVand everyone stands up,
p41
aVand the partner running the meeting starts looking really embarrassed.
p42
aVAnd I realized he doesn't know where the women's room is in his office.
