aa(lp54
VSo the question is, how are we going to fix this?
p55
aVHow do we change these numbers at the top?
p56
aVHow do we make this different?
p57
aVI want to start out by saying, I talk about this \u2014
p58
aVabout keeping women in the workforce \u2014
p59
aVbecause I really think that's the answer.
p60
aVIn the high-income part of our workforce,
p61
aVin the people who end up at the top \u2014
p62
aVFortune 500 CEO jobs, or the equivalent in other industries \u2014
p63
aVthe problem, I am convinced, is that women are dropping out.
p64
aVNow people talk about this a lot,
p65
aVand they talk about things like flextime and mentoring
p66
aVand programs companies should have to train women.
p67
aVI want to talk about none of that today,
p68
aVeven though that's all really important.
p69
aVToday I want to focus on what we can do as individuals.
p70
aVWhat are the messages we need to tell ourselves?
p71
aVWhat are the messages we tell the women that work with and for us?
p72
aVWhat are the messages we tell our daughters?
p73
aa(lp74
VNow, at the outset, I want to be very clear
p75
aVthat this speech comes with no judgments.
p76
aVI don't have the right answer.
p77
aVI don't even have it for myself.
p78
aVI left San Francisco, where I live, on Monday,
p79
aVand I was getting on the plane for this conference.
p80
aVAnd my daughter, who's three, when I dropped her off at preschool,
p81
aVdid that whole hugging-the-leg, crying, "Mommy, don't get on the plane" thing.
p82
aVThis is hard. I feel guilty sometimes.
p83
aVI know no women,
p84
aVwhether they're at home or whether they're in the workforce,
p85
aVwho don't feel that sometimes.
p86
aVSo I'm not saying that staying in the workforce
p87
aVis the right thing for everyone.
p88
aa(lp89
VMy talk today is about what the messages are
p90
aVif you do want to stay in the workforce,
p91
aVand I think there are three.
p92
aVOne, sit at the table.
p93
aVTwo, make your partner a real partner.
p94
aVAnd three, don't leave before you leave.
p95
aVNumber one: sit at the table.
p96
aVJust a couple weeks ago at Facebook,
p97
aVwe hosted a very senior government official,
p98
aVand he came in to meet with senior execs
p99
aVfrom around Silicon Valley.
p100
aVAnd everyone kind of sat at the table.
p101
aVHe had these two women who were traveling with him
p102
aVpretty senior in his department,
p103
aVand I kind of said to them,
p104
aV"Sit at the table. Come on, sit at the table,"
p105
aVand they sat on the side of the room.
p106
aVWhen I was in college, my senior year,
p107
aVI took a course called European Intellectual History.
p108
aVDon't you love that kind of thing from college?
p109
aVI wish I could do that now.
p110
aVAnd I took it with my roommate, Carrie,
p111
aVwho was then a brilliant literary student \u2014
p112
aVand went on to be a brilliant literary scholar \u2014
p113
aVand my brother \u2014 smart guy,
p114
aVbut a water-polo-playing pre-med,
p115
aVwho was a sophomore.
p116
aa(lp117
VThe three of us take this class together.
p118
aVAnd then Carrie reads all the books in the original Greek and Latin,
p119
aVgoes to all the lectures.
p120
aVI read all the books in English
p121
aVand go to most of the lectures.
p122
aVMy brother is kind of busy.
p123
aVHe reads one book of 12 and goes to a couple of lectures,
p124
aVmarches himself up to our room
p125
aVa couple days before the exam to get himself tutored.
p126
aVThe three of us go to the exam together, and we sit down.
p127
aVAnd we sit there for three hours \u2014
p128
aVand our little blue notebooks \u2014 yes, I'm that old.
p129
aVWe walk out, we look at each other, and we say, "How did you do?"
p130
aVAnd Carrie says, "Boy, I feel like I didn't really draw out the main point
p131
aVon the Hegelian dialectic."
p132
aVAnd I say, "God, I really wish I had really connected
p133
aVJohn Locke's theory of property with the philosophers that follow."
p134
aVAnd my brother says,
p135
aV"I got the top grade in the class."
