aa(lp289
VMessage number three:
p290
aVDon't leave before you leave.
p291
aVI think there's a really deep irony
p292
aVto the fact that actions women are taking \u2014
p293
aVand I see this all the time \u2014
p294
aVwith the objective of staying in the workforce
p295
aVactually lead to their eventually leaving.
p296
aVHere's what happens:
p297
aVWe're all busy. Everyone's busy. A woman's busy.
p298
aVAnd she starts thinking about having a child,
p299
aVand from the moment she starts thinking about having a child,
p300
aVshe starts thinking about making room for that child.
p301
aV"How am I going to fit this into everything else I'm doing?"
p302
aVAnd literally from that moment,
p303
aVshe doesn't raise her hand anymore,
p304
aVshe doesn't look for a promotion, she doesn't take on the new project,
p305
aVshe doesn't say, "Me. I want to do that."
p306
aVShe starts leaning back.
p307
aVThe problem is that \u2014
p308
aVlet's say she got pregnant that day, that day \u2014
p309
aVnine months of pregnancy, three months of maternity leave,
p310
aVsix months to catch your breath \u2014
p311
aVFast-forward two years,
p312
aVmore often \u2014 and as I've seen it \u2014
p313
aVwomen start thinking about this way earlier \u2014
p314
aVwhen they get engaged, or married,
p315
aVwhen they start thinking about having a child,
p316
aVwhich can take a long time.
p317
aVOne woman came to see me about this.
p318
aVShe looked a little young.
p319
aVAnd I said, "So are you and your husband thinking about having a baby?"
p320
aVAnd she said, "Oh no, I'm not married."
p321
aVShe didn't even have a boyfriend.
p322
aa(lp323
V(Laughter)
p324
aa(lp325
VI said, "You're thinking about this just way too early."
p326
aa(lp327
VBut the point is that what happens
p328
aVonce you start kind of quietly leaning back?
p329
aVEveryone who's been through this \u2014
p330
aVand I'm here to tell you, once you have a child at home,
p331
aVyour job better be really good to go back,
p332
aVbecause it's hard to leave that kid at home.
p333
aVYour job needs to be challenging.
p334
aVIt needs to be rewarding.
p335
aVYou need to feel like you're making a difference.
p336
aVAnd if two years ago you didn't take a promotion
p337
aVand some guy next to you did,
p338
aVif three years ago you stopped looking for new opportunities,
p339
aVyou're going to be bored
p340
aVbecause you should have kept your foot on the gas pedal.
p341
aVDon't leave before you leave.
p342
aVStay in.
p343
aVKeep your foot on the gas pedal,
p344
aVuntil the very day you need to leave to take a break for a child \u2014
p345
aVand then make your decisions.
p346
aVDon't make decisions too far in advance,
p347
aVparticularly ones you're not even conscious you're making.
p348
aa(lp349
VMy generation really, sadly,
p350
aVis not going to change the numbers at the top.
p351
aVThey're just not moving.
p352
aVWe are not going to get to where 50 percent of the population \u2014
p353
aVin my generation, there will not be 50 percent of [women]
p354
aVat the top of any industry.
p355
aVBut I'm hopeful that future generations can.
p356
aVI think a world where half of our countries and our companies
p357
aVwere run by women, would be a better world.
p358
aVIt's not just because people would know where the women's bathrooms are,
p359
aVeven though that would be very helpful.
p360
aVI think it would be a better world.
p361
aVI have two children.
p362
aVI have a five-year-old son and a two-year-old daughter.
p363
aVI want my son to have a choice
p364
aVto contribute fully in the workforce or at home,
p365
aVand I want my daughter to have the choice to not just succeed,
p366
aVbut to be liked for her accomplishments.
